{"Body": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: right; font: 13.0px 'Helvetica Neue'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} span.s1 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->Ryan Bartlett\n\nJS Theoretical Physics\n\nPresident\n\nIt&rsquo;s widely assumed that Ryan Bartlett has been planning a run for SU President since he was elected class rep in his first year. Now in third year, the theoretical physics student is following through on this long held ambition.\n\nBartlett has been omnipresent on campus since his first year and, this year, has done the seemingly impossible by increasing his extra-curricular workload. Such is his inclination to be present at college events, Bartlett has reportedly recruited note-takers from his class to ensure that his implicit electioneering doesn&rsquo;t take too heavy a toll on his degree.\n\nThe Englishman, who&rsquo;ll turn twenty-one on the first day of campaigning, has been onvolved in sports clubs, student societies and the SU. He&rsquo;s served as PRO and Intermediates Manager for the GAA club and as men&rsquo;s captain of the swimming and water polo club. He was on the organising committee for RAG Week, the SU campaigns committee, the education committee and the Joint Executive of the SU. Reflecting his international credentials, Bartlett was also the International Students Officer of the SU as well as the convenor for the EMS faculty.\n\nWhile this list is by no means exhaustive, it serves to highlight the work ethic that has made Bartlett an invaluable presence to those in the SU who count on enthusiastic volunteers to implement policy.\n\nBartlett feels that his experience has allowed him to learn from the mistakes of past Presidents. &ldquo;With my experience comes the ability to put the issues in context and find solutions that work,&rdquo; says Bartlett. &ldquo;One of the most important changes that should be implemented in the Students&rsquo; Union is to make it more transparent to all students.&rdquo;\n\n&ldquo;There are many simple changes that could make a massive improvement to the lives of students in college. For example, I am currently working on getting timetables put up on the doors of computer rooms, so students can see when they are free.&rdquo;\n\nOne issue that has vexed many involved in sporting clubs in recent years is the lack of student input on what student contributions to the Department of Sport are spent. Bartlett believes that &ldquo;the student contribution can no longer be allowed to spaghettified into a black hole.&rdquo;", "Imageurl": "<!-- p.p1 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: right; font: 13.0px 'Helvetica Neue'} p.p2 {margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; text-align: justify; text-indent: 10.0px; font: 9.0px 'Whitney HTF'} span.s1 {letter-spacing: -0.1px} -->Ryan Bartlett\n\nJS Theoretical Physics\n\nPresident\n\nIt&rsquo;s widely assumed that Ryan Bartlett has been planning a run for SU President since he was elected class rep in his first year. Now in third year, the theoretical physics student is following through on this long held ambition.\n\nBartlett has been omnipresent on campus since his first year and, this year, has done the seemingly impossible by increasing his extra-curricular workload. Such is his inclination to be present at college events, Bartlett has reportedly recruited note-takers from his class to ensure that his implicit electioneering doesn&rsquo;t take too heavy a toll on his degree.\n\nThe Englishman, who&rsquo;ll turn twenty-one on the first day of campaigning, has been onvolved in sports clubs, student societies and the SU. He&rsquo;s served as PRO and Intermediates Manager for the GAA club and as men&rsquo;s captain of the swimming and water polo club. He was on the organising committee for RAG Week, the SU campaigns committee, the education committee and the Joint Executive of the SU. Reflecting his international credentials, Bartlett was also the International Students Officer of the SU as well as the convenor for the EMS faculty.\n\nWhile this list is by no means exhaustive, it serves to highlight the work ethic that has made Bartlett an invaluable presence to those in the SU who count on enthusiastic volunteers to implement policy.\n\nBartlett feels that his experience has allowed him to learn from the mistakes of past Presidents. &ldquo;With my experience comes the ability to put the issues in context and find solutions that work,&rdquo; says Bartlett. &ldquo;One of the most important changes that should be implemented in the Students&rsquo; Union is to make it more transparent to all students.&rdquo;\n\n&ldquo;There are many simple changes that could make a massive improvement to the lives of students in college. For example, I am currently working on getting timetables put up on the doors of computer rooms, so students can see when they are free.&rdquo;\n\nOne issue that has vexed many involved in sporting clubs in recent years is the lack of student input on what student contributions to the Department of Sport are spent. Bartlett believes that &ldquo;the student contribution can no longer be allowed to spaghettified into a black hole.&rdquo;", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "221", "Heading": "SU ELECTION CANDIDATE: Ryan Bartlett"}